# claude-content-writer

A comprehensive Claude Code skill that writes blog articles, social media posts (LinkedIn, Facebook, Twitter, Instagram), email newsletters, and SEO metadata that sound like a specific human wrote them — not like AI generated them.

## What it does

Install this skill and Claude Code gains the ability to:

- **Write content for any platform:** Blog articles, LinkedIn posts, Facebook posts, Instagram captions, tweets, Twitter threads, and email newsletters
- **Generate SEO metadata:** Complete meta tags, Open Graph tags, Twitter Cards, and schema markup
- **Research before writing:** Analyze URLs, gather insights, and create research briefs
- **Manage your content profile:** Store and update writer profiles, products/services, CTAs, and case studies
- **Create content packages:** Produce coordinated multi-platform content from a single brief
- **Review and humanize drafts:** Identify and eliminate AI writing patterns
- **Remember everything:** Brand, voice, CTAs, case studies, and preferences across sessions

Every draft goes through a built-in anti-AI audit before delivery. The goal is content that reads like a specific person wrote it, not like a language model was asked to write about a topic.

---

## Installation

```bash
npm install -g claude-content-writer
```

The postinstall script copies the skill files to `~/.claude/skills/content-writer/`. Claude Code picks them up automatically on next launch — no config required.

---

## How it works

The skill has three modes:

### 1. Onboarding (first use)

On first use, Claude runs a structured interview across 6 areas:

| Area | What gets captured |
|---|---|
| Identity & business | Name, title, company, audience, industry |
| Voice & tone | Adjectives, influences, things to avoid |
| Content strategy | Types, themes, goals, article length |
| Case studies | Projects, outcomes, metrics, NDA constraints |
| CTAs & shortcodes | Links, booking URLs, shortcode definitions |
| Formatting & publishing | Output format, platform, timing workflow |

After the interview, Claude summarizes the profile and saves it to memory. Every future session reads from this profile — you don't repeat yourself.

### 2. Production (content creation)

With a profile in memory, Claude:

1. Determines content type (blog, social post, SEO metadata, etc.)
2. Reads platform-specific conventions and anti-AI checklist
3. Loads your profile, products, CTAs, and case studies from memory
4. Fetches live samples from your blog URL (if provided) to calibrate voice
5. Researches the topic (if URL provided or requested)
6. Plans the piece: angle, case study selection, data points, CTA placement
7. Writes the draft following platform conventions
8. Runs a two-pass anti-AI audit and revises
9. Delivers the finished content with publishing notes

### 3. Management (profile & assets)

Manage your content infrastructure:

- **Profile management:** Create, view, edit, or delete your writer profile
- **Product/service management:** Add, view, edit, or delete products/services to reference in content
- **CTA management:** Add, view, edit, or delete call-to-action templates for different platforms
- **Case study management:** Add, view, edit, or delete case studies with rotation tracking

---

## Usage

Once installed, just talk to Claude Code naturally:

**Content creation:**
```
write a blog post about why most SaaS onboarding fails
create a Twitter thread about MVP validation
write an Instagram caption for this product launch
generate SEO metadata for my latest article
create a Facebook post about our case study
LinkedIn post about our new pricing model
content package on our Helm case study (creates blog + social + newsletter)
```

**Research:**
```
research this topic before writing: [URL or topic]
analyze this article and create content from it: [URL]
```

**Profile management:**
```
create my writer profile
view my profile
edit my voice description
add a new product to my profile
add a CTA for LinkedIn
add this case study: [details]
view all my case studies
```

**Review and humanize:**
```
humanize this draft [paste content]
review this for AI tells [paste content]
```

Claude recognizes these requests and routes them through the skill automatically.

