## Content packages

Ask for a "content package" and Claude produces multiple formats from a single brief:

**Standard package (blog + LinkedIn + newsletter):**
1. **Blog article** — the anchor piece, full length
2. **LinkedIn post** — adapted for the feed, not just a link share
3. **Email newsletter** — platform-ready with subject line options

**Full social package (all platforms):**
1. Blog article
2. LinkedIn post
3. Facebook post
4. Instagram caption
5. Twitter thread
6. SEO metadata
7. Email newsletter

**Custom packages:**
Specify which platforms you want, and Claude creates content for each with consistent messaging adapted to each platform's conventions.

All pieces are delivered as separate files with publishing sequence notes and platform-specific recommendations.

---

## Platform-specific conventions

Each platform has unique conventions and best practices:

- **Blog articles:** 1,500-2,500 words, H2 structure, embedded CTAs, SEO optimization
- **LinkedIn:** 1,400-1,800 characters, bold headers, link in first comment
- **Facebook:** 100-250 characters for reach, link in first comment, conversational tone
- **Instagram:** 125-150 chars (short) or 1,000-2,200 chars (story), 3-5 hashtags, "link in bio"
- **Twitter:** 240-280 characters (tweets), 5-12 tweets (threads), no external links in body
- **SEO metadata:** Title tags (50-60 chars), meta descriptions (150-160 chars), OG tags, schema markup

Claude automatically adapts your voice and message to each platform's conventions.

---

## Voice fidelity

The skill fetches published articles from your blog URL to calibrate sentence patterns, vocabulary level, and personality — not just general tone. If you don't have a blog, it calibrates from the voice description captured during onboarding.

The anti-AI audit eliminates specific patterns: parallel list structures, rule-of-three constructions, throat-clearing openers, high-frequency AI vocabulary (leverage, seamless, robust, pivotal, etc.), em dash overuse, and generic conclusions. The checklist is based on Wikipedia's "Signs of AI writing" guide and is applied to every draft before delivery.

---

## Research workflow

Before writing, Claude can research your topic:

1. **From URLs:** Provide a URL and Claude analyzes it, extracts insights, and creates content inspired by (not copied from) the source
2. **From topics:** Ask Claude to research a topic and it will search for sources, extract insights, and organize findings
3. **Research briefs:** Claude creates structured research briefs with key insights, contrarian angles, and proof points

Research ensures your content is grounded in data, includes specific examples, and offers unique perspectives.

---

## Updating your profile

Tell Claude to update your profile at any time:

```
remember that we no longer reference the Acme project in content
change my booking link to cal.com/newlink
add this case study: [paste details]
we stopped using Mailchimp, switch to Beehiiv
```

Claude updates the relevant memory entries and uses the new information in all future sessions.

---

## Shortcodes

Define shortcodes during onboarding for CTA links and recurring text blocks:

```
{{booking_link}}   → https://cal.com/yourname
{{cta:soft}}       → your standard soft close paragraph
{{case_study:acme}} → https://yourdomain.com/case-study/acme
```

By default, Claude expands shortcodes to actual URLs in the draft. If you use a CMS that handles substitution, tell Claude to leave them as placeholders instead.

